        <h2 id="what-is">What is Surfer SEO?</h2>
        <p>Surfer SEO is a content optimisation platform built around a Google Docs-style editor. You paste a target keyword and a draft; Surfer scores your draft against the top-10 ranking pages on a 0–100 scale, suggests missing terms, recommends ideal word count, and flags heading and structure gaps.</p>

        <p>The core suite does five things:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Content Editor</strong> — real-time scoring with NLP term suggestions and structure recommendations</li>
          <li><strong>SERP Analyzer</strong> — deep analysis of 500+ on-page signals across top-ranking pages</li>
          <li><strong>Keyword Research</strong> — topical clusters, intent classification, search volume</li>
          <li><strong>Audit</strong> — analyses existing pages and suggests on-page improvements</li>
          <li><strong>Surfer AI</strong> — generates an optimised first draft from a single keyword (Scale AI plan)</li>
        </ol>

        <p>What Surfer is <em>not</em>: a backlink tool, a rank tracker, or a publishing platform. It tells you what to write and helps you write it. Getting it published — and getting links to it — is still on you.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">ℹ️ Company background</div>
          <p>Surfer was founded in 2017 in Wrocław, Poland by Sławek Czajkowski and Lucjan Suski. The company is profitable, has raised modest seed funding, and now serves over 150,000 users across SMBs, in-house teams, and SEO agencies. The product is run by an SEO-native team — which shows in how opinionated the Content Editor is.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="features">Surfer SEO features — the full 2026 walkthrough</h2>
        <p>The feature surface is focused. Here is what actually matters in daily use, broken down by tool.</p>

        <h3>1. Content Editor — the reason you buy Surfer</h3>
        <p>The Content Editor is the headline product. Enter a keyword, pick a country, and Surfer pulls the top-10 ranking pages, extracts the patterns that correlate with rank, and gives you a live Content Score as you type.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Live Content Score</strong> — 0–100, updates with every keystroke</li>
          <li><strong>Term suggestions</strong> — NLP-extracted phrases the top results use, with target frequencies</li>
          <li><strong>Structure guidance</strong> — recommended word count, heading count, paragraph length, image count</li>
          <li><strong>Outline builder</strong> — auto-generates H2/H3 suggestions pulled from competitor pages</li>
          <li><strong>Plagiarism check</strong> — built into the editor, no separate tool needed</li>
          <li><strong>Google Docs add-on</strong> — same scoring, same suggestions, inside Docs</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The 0.28 correlation between Content Score and ranking position is the highest of any optimisation tool we benchmarked. Translation: it works.</p>

        <h3>2. SERP Analyzer — the engine under the editor</h3>
        <p>Goes deeper than the editor. Pulls 500+ on-page signals from the top-10 results: word count, exact-match keyword density, heading structure, image count, schema markup, page speed, internal links. Useful when the Content Editor's recommendations feel off and you want the raw competitor data.</p>

        <h3>3. Keyword Research — added in 2022</h3>
        <p>Newer than the editor and less mature than Ahrefs or Semrush. Strengths: topical clustering is genuinely useful for planning a content pillar. Weaknesses: search volume data lags premium tools by 2–4 weeks, and the keyword universe is smaller. Pair with Ahrefs or Semrush if you do serious research.</p>

        <h3>4. Audit — fix existing pages</h3>
        <p>Point Audit at an underperforming URL and Surfer compares it against the current top-10, surfacing missing terms, structural gaps, and on-page issues. The single most under-used feature — most teams ignore it and keep writing new content when refreshing old posts would lift rankings faster.</p>

        <h3>5. Surfer AI — full-draft generation</h3>
        <p>On the Scale AI plan, Surfer AI generates a 1,500–3,000-word draft from a single keyword. The output is decent — well-structured, on-topic, hits the Content Score target. It is not publishable as-is. Plan on 30–60 minutes of human editing per article (fact-checks, examples, voice, EEAT signals). Useful as a structured first draft; not a replacement for writers.</p>

